html: 7.21.24  3:39 am   These days I tend to get maybe about 1.5 minutes into writing a song no problem before hitting walls, because at that point writing further can become time consuming and maybe even tedious, since usually you have to do full run throughs and hope the ether gives you what happens next. I will say I hit that wall in writing today and tried that idea of making it bad on purpose, and it literally completely worked and propelled the whole thing forward into the right direction. I think the idea works because fundamentally good songs play, like play around, and trying something bad to throw a wrench in the whole thing is sometimes the right chaos and the order / clean up that follows feels so good. Kinda weird. Would you agree with that, or do you think it's silly to try to figure out the secret sauce behind the secret sauce of trying something bad on purpose
